Well to the point here is the info I found about how some of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>          Building</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>          Siege</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> work:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>          A guild starts by collecting massive amounts of gold, enough for a Tree of Life and hopefully a few buildings around it. Anyone with enough money can build a building -- not just a guild leader. <br>
<br>
The guild continues to make revenue, spending it on advancing their buildings in &quot;ranks&quot; just like players, from ranks 1 to 7.<br>
<br>
Each rank gives the owner of the building (who is the one who built it -- not always the guild leader) more NPC trainers/shopkeepers, more options and more &quot;production slots.&quot; More on that in a minute.<br>
<br>
Barracks allow you to create several different types of Guard Captian. A few examples being Captian, Archmage, Master Archer and so on. Each guard and capt, just like buildings, are ranked 1-7, (which is level 10-70 remember) increasing the rank of the barracks increases the level of your NPC guards.<br>
<br>
Guards can be given options such as waypoints/patrol routes, KOS/non-KOS lists, and will only act under the authority of who owns the barracks. (again not always the guild leader) This could even lead to civil wars in less disciplined guilds.<br>
<br>
Other buildings, such as the forge, has shopkeeper/production NPCs. They gave us this example of blacksmithing:<br>
A character with the blacksmith discipline builds a forge. The character then accesses the NPC(s) within and tells him, for example &quot;make me 4 swords.&quot; Each item takes up a production slot -- I beleive the starting level is four.<br>
These items will take time and gold to produce. When the owner comes back, the NPC gives the building owner a report of what could be made. So let's say he makes a &quot;Sword of crappiness,&quot; a &quot;Sword of Uberness,&quot; and a &quot;longsword.&quot; The quality and the frequency of good items depends on your smith's level, and your forge's rank. The owning player could then choose for the NPC to make (and therefore buy) the good items and discard (and not be charged at all) the low-quality ones.<br>
<br>
Now, how to seige!<br>
<br>
A Tree of Life does two things: allows you a place to respawn, and literally is the heart of your city. It works by providing a HP/second healing on all buildings within the radius of the tree. Like all things in SB, this can be upgraded to improve both the range and amount of building healing. This tree can be controlled at anytime by the guild leader to redistribute the healing. (and during a seige it would act as a &quot;fire hose&quot; effect) If the guild leader dies by any cause, he loses this ability for one hour.<br>
<br>
Attackers may build a war tent so they may also work in shifts. A seige attacker that dies still respawns at his ToL, but an attacker may go to the tent and log out. (if he needs to leave the game for awhile) Providing the tent is still standing, when he/she logs back in, they will be at the war tent.<br>
<br>
In addition to this, attackers may build a seige tent, which will produce an engineer. This NPC builds seige engines (catapults, trebuchets and ballistas) at the owner's command. There is nothing to stop the beseiged from doing this and firing from inside the walls, either. A seige ends when either the attackers are driven off or the tree is destroyed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  MORE INFO</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 4/11:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  -You pick a Race<br>
-You pick a character Path<br>
-You pick a Class<br>
--These things will determine your starting Attributes, Skills, Combat Powers, Special Abilities, beginning Weapon Specs, starting equipment and equipment availability, starting safehold city<br>
<br>
Then you begin play in your starting safehold, which is a place you can live out of for your 1st 20 levels, and is adjacent to experience and hunting areas that are safe from PvP warfare. Or, you can venture to your Guild's main city if you wish at any time. Or explore deeper into the dangerous world, though survival would be doubtful.<br>
<br>
As you level you will earn Character Points that can be spent to increase all qualities of the Character.<br>
<br>
Eventually, at certain key levels (the exact levels have not been told to us yet, some people speculate at levels 10, 20, 30, or perhaps 10, 25, 40) you will have the chance to enhance your character in many ways through training in a new Discipline. A Discipline is almost as important a choice as your Class. It will open new things to your Character that your base Class never had (new equipment options, new skills, etc.).<br>
<br>
Consider taking a Discipline to be like guiding your Character down a certain new branch of development; like a new career that adds to your Character. Each available Disc is very specific in nature.<br>
<br>
You will, however, need to be careful how you spend your Character Points. You will not have enough CP to master all available skills from all 3 available Disciplines that you can take during your Character's life.<br>
<br>
Some people are of the opinion that taking more than 1 or 2 Disc is foolish since you could spread your Character too thin...and know many skills, but at a lower level of proficiency. Others, myself included, will tell you to take all 3, because they will probably provide certain bonuses automatically; and then you will just have to be careful not to spend your points all over the place.<br>
<br>
Some Classes, Disciplines and other things are restricted, locked and hidden from the players as they begin the game. Only exploration and questing will open these up to you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
