<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> CITIES</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Will all towns be owned by a Guild?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
No, not all of the Cities or towns in Shadowbane will be built and owned by players. Some static communities will be managed and run by the Game Administrators. <br>
<br>
Player-run Guilds have the ability to close their towns off from strangers, declaring them to be &quot;members only.&quot; For defensive reasons, many Guilds will. There are also, however, a large number of in-game reasons to keep a City as open as possible. Well-stocked Shops with competent Vendors and Tradesmen can become a tremendous source of income. Guild Leaders can also levy a tax on all buildings within their City, taking gold in exchange for access to the powers of the City's Tree of Life. The Guild leadership and the building owner must both agree on the level of the tax, and the Guild Leadership also decides how much access non-members will get to their Town's resources. These economic  policies will be important decisions for the Guild Leaders and Inner Councils to make. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What is the difference between a Guild Run Town and a GM Run Town?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
At a purely structural level, they're identical. Both types of city-states can include all of the things you would normally expect to find in a fantasy medieval town - weapon shops, armor shops, guard barracks, city walls, guildhalls, you name it. The only inherent difference between the two is that Guild-Run City-States allow players to set the policies (and tax rates) and can grow or decline in power over time. Also, some GM run towns are designated as Safeholds, areas in which PvP combat is absolutely prohibited. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What exactly are City-States, Provinces, and Nations?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A City-State</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is a city controlled by a player-run Guild that stands on its own, owing allegiance to no one. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A Province</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is a city controlled by a player-run Guild that has pledged fealty to another, and now exists as part of a larger Nation. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A Nation</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is a City controlled by a player-run Guild that has one or more Provinces who have sworn fealty to it. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Will there be enough towns for every Guild to have one?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
While there will likely be a relatively large number of Guilds in Shadowbane, there will be a limited number of player controlled City-States in the game. Most player Guilds will have to swear fealty to another Guild or Kingdom initially, until they can amass enough wealth or strength to take their own town. <br>
<br>
City-states will remain in short supply by design, promoting competition and conflict among Guilds. Of course, if City-States become too few, we at Wolfpack can always add new world fragments to the game, each with a new quota of player City-States. Shadowbane's random world generating features make this process particularly fast and easy. <br>
<br>
*This would be a good reason to start forming a strong guild early <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How do I protect my Tree and my City?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
There are a large number of defensive measures and structures that can be acquired in-game to help defend your Town or City. NPC Guards can be recruited to patrol your streets, and alert Archers can man your ramparts. Castle walls can be raised to fortify the perimeter and Runemasters can brought in to nurture and protect the Tree of Life. Guild Leaders will also generate and control a “Kill on Sight” list, informing the Guards which players or player-run Guilds are be considered Enemies of the State. <br>
<br>
The best defense of all, though, is a Guild's relationship with other players. Diplomacy can be a far keener weapon than any sword, and intrigue can often accomplish more than conflict.  Banner men and political allegiance will weigh heavily in the balance of feudal power.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> t type of structures can I build?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Players can build a wide variety of potential structures, from Barracks to Guild Halls.  Each building has a specific purpose, providing City dwellers with goods or services, and the Building owners with wealth amassed through the profit made in each sale.<br>
<br>
*Details on buildings here <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://shadowbane.ubisoft.com/worldinfo/citybuilding/index.shtml">shadowbane.ubisoft.com/worldinfo/citybuilding/index.shtml</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  are Buildings classified?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Every Building in Shadowbane can be classified by three basic attributes: the Building's Type, Rank, and Stage.<br>
<br>
Type refers to the Building's ultimate purpose, and determines which types of Tradesmen and Hirelings can be assigned to it. A Weaponsmith can't produce his wares in a Tavern, for example.  He requires a Forge.<br>
<br>
Rank is similar to the Rank characters have: think of it as the rough measure of a Building's &quot;level.&quot; Rank measures how well-outfitted and equipped the building is, and the basic characteristics of a Building (structural hit points, etc) improve each time its Rank increases. All Buildings begin at Rank One, and take time and money to upgrade. A Building can hold one Tradesman for each rank it has, and as the Rank of a Building increases, any Tradesmen within it will work more quickly and efficiently.<br>
<br>
Stage is a byproduct of Rank, and along with the Type, determines the actual appearance of a Building. Most Buildings in Shadowbane have three distinct Stages, and at each successive Stage the Building grows larger and more ornate. Buildings change to Stage Two at Rank Three, and transform into Stage Three buildings at Rank Five. Guild Halls are the only Buildings that lack distinct Stages: they are built at the peak of their beauty, and their appearance never changes, regardless of their Rank.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How do i build a structure?<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <br>
<br>
To build a Building, a Character must commission and purchase a Deed from an Architect (a specialized form of NPC Hireling), then activate the Deed to place the new structure. The purchaser of the Deed is thereafter the owner of the Building, and has total control over the production of the Tradesmen assigned to it. In the future, a character can relinquish ownership of a Building to another character if they so desire. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Who owns the building me or m</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Whatever character activates the Deed is the sole owner of the building.  The Owner's Guild has no direct control over anything the building produces (although members are always well advised to follow the wishes of their Guild).  Note that the owner of a building can direct the Tradesmen who work there to give special pricing to fellow Guild and Nation members.  In this case, the benefit is received by members of the building owners Guild, not necessarily the Guild that controls the city. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How does item production work?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Once the owner of a Building installs an appropriate Tradesman, the owner can then direct the Tradesman's activities, giving him a list of items to create and setting the profit margins for all goods and services sold at that building.  There are three different profit margins available; one for Nation members, one for fellow Guild Members, and one for everyone else. Once again, Nation and Guild refer to the affiliation of the Building owner, not necessarily the Guild that runs the City. <br>
