<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Screenshots of Siege</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://shadowbane.ubisoft.com/downloads/screenshots/200008/index.shtml">shadowbane.ubisoft.com/downloads/screenshots/200008/index.shtml</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Can I lay siege to another guild’s town?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Yes, you can. A word of warning, however – as you might expect, the burden of work definitely falls on the aggressor. It’s much easier to defend a castle than it is to attack one. Sieges are long and arduous affairs, potentially requiring days or even weeks of real time before any significant headway is made.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How long does it take to Siege a City?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It depends, of course, on the size of the force attempting to take over or destroy the City and the size of the defending force, coupled with the City's defenses. Successful sieges will normally take 24 or more hours to accomplish.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Why do Sieges take that long?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
First, Buildings are hard to destroy, and a Tree of Life can heal buildings, in some cases as quickly as attackers can damage them.  Don't forget, all the while you are trying to take over or destroy a City, the Guild and/or Nation who owns it will be fighting back - a complete City is a monumental investment of time and gold, and any Guild will fight tooth and nail to defend it.  The final reason is playabilty. It would hardly be fair (or fun) for the city a Guild has invested so much in to be taken over or destroyed overnight, while all its members were offline or asleep.<br>
