<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How is a Tree of Life neutralized?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The besieging force must construct a Bane Circle within a certain distance of the Tree of Life.  The Bane Circle gradually leeches energy from the Tree of Life until the Tree has no more power, in effect neutralizing it and removing its healing power from the target City's defense.  If the Bane Circle is destroyed before the process is complete, the Tree of Life will gradually (not instantly) reclaim it's lost power. Sorties out of a besieged City to break a Bane Circle will be an essential part of any City's defense, although once they leave the shelter of the walls, the defenders will be fair game for the attacking force.<br>
<br>
Other spells and powers can poison a Tree of Life, diminishing its energy and reducing its effectiveness for a long period of time. Usually, these spells are unleashed upon a Tree of Life just before a Siege begins, and are a sure sign of imminent attack.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How can I destroy a Building?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Attack it. Buildings are extremely durable and a Tree of Life can heal them as quickly as they're damaged. Without truly devastating firepower, most Building are beyond a character's power to destroy.  That is why many Guilds attempting to besiege a City utilize Siege Engines.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What are Siege Engines?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Siege Engines are medieval devices, essentially primitive artillery used to hurl heavy projectiles at a target or to batter down walls and gates.  In Shadowbane, Siege Engines can be built by specialized Hirelings (known as Engineers), and are used to batter Cities into rubble. Guilds will have access to four different types of Siege Engines:  Ballistas, Battering Rams, Mangonels, and Trebuchets.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What Role can Guards and Archers play during a Siege?<br>
<br>
Although they cannot leave their home City as part of an attacking army, Guard Captains, Magisters, Master Archers and their minions will defend the Town they belong to, acting as additional Guild members for the defenders.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Without Permanent Death, how can you hope to win?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You can destroy the Tree of Life, taking the Guild with it. If you manage to destroy a Town, you've crippled them economically. Remember - slain characters don't come back at full strength. Guild Sieges are wars of attrition. Eventually something has to give…<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> If attackers restart all the way back at their home City, how can they hope to compete?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
They don't necessarily have to. Special War Tents can be built that allow besiegers to log out or back in or near the besieged City (a function similar to that of Inns).  Death, however, is a different matter, and carries harsher penalties. If an attacker is slain, he will still respawn at his or her Guild's Tree of Life.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> If defenders respawn at their Tree as soon as they are killed, how can they lose?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
People &quot;reclothed in flesh&quot; at a Tree of Life don't come back at full strength: at the very least they will need to recover their Health and Stamina, and will function as if they were lower level characters for a period of time (the &quot;Shroud of Shadow&quot; mentioned above). They may also lose some of their equipment, as the number of bondable items is limited. The effect of the Shroud becomes more severe if a character is killed a second time before they recover: people killed over and over again become practically useless. Also, even a minute can be a long time to go without the powers and skills of a powerful Guild member. Death in Shadowbane is not permanent, but a timely death can turn the tide of a battle.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Isn't it too hard to destroy a city?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Remember, a City is a massive investment on the part of an entire Guild - if they were easy to destroy, wars and conflicts would lose their meaning. Defenders definitely have the advantage, and &quot;total wars&quot; to the death should never be undertaken lightly. It would probably take a coalition of Guilds working together to topple a decent-sized city. Smaller raids, to destroy one or two strategic buildings, are much more feasible. Of course, even if such a raid is successful, the injured Guild will certainly retaliate... <br>
<br>
*unlike DAoC in Shadowbane when you destroy/takeover a city or even just 1 building its a BIG deal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What happens when the Tree of Life is destroyed?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The Guild that controlled the Tree of Life and any Guilds that declared fealty to that guild become &quot;Errant Guilds.&quot; All members of these guilds will respawn to a Tree of Life in a Safehold until they can bond to another Guild Tree.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What is an Errant Guild?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
An Errant Guild is a Guild that is neither a Landed Guild (directly controls a Tree of Life) nor a Sworn Guild (extensions of a Landed Guild and are given preferential access to City facilities).  An Errant Guild does not receive any of bonuses that a Landed or Sworn Guild receives from its affiliation to a Tree of Life. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What are my chances of taking over the World?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To be honest, no one knows.  It’s certainly possible.  Can one Guild do it?  Maybe.  A coalition of Guilds working together?  More likely.  What’s the best recipe for world domination:  Coercion?  Political ruthlessness? Economic might? Real life philosophers and James Bond supervillains have been asking that question for centuries. In Shadowbane, as in the real world, the answer remains unclear. It's up to you, the players, to try and find out...<br>
<br>
You can certainly change the World, but taking it over is another matter entirely.  One thing IS quite certain, however. In Shadowbane, for the first time, you can actually try.<br>
