<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Will there be Player-versus-Player (PvP) combat?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Yes, Shadowbane has been built from the ground up to support Player-versus-Player combat (in fact, some might say that the game's backstory actively encourages it).  In addition to PvP, we have also implemented many game mechanics to support Guild-versus-Guild (GvG) and Kingdom-versus-Kingdom (KvK) combat.<br>
<br>
This isn't to say, however, that our PvP Combat is unrestricted -- The game is territory based, with lands ranging from completely protected (such as the Newbie Areas and Starting Cities) to extremely dangerous (hostile advanced areas and land held by enemy nations).<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What about Player Killing?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
We have worked very hard to ensure that the combat system fits within the context of the game world.  Pointless violence is not the purpose of Shadowbane: but we also assert that it's hard to tell a gripping story (especially a gripping fantasy story) without conflict or battles at all. We remain firm believers that not only can PvP and Roleplaying go hand in hand, but that, in fact, the pinnacle of each can only be achieved when the two exist in tandem. Without the power to back up your words, what good is a well-acted swagger? And how much more meaningful will your character's victories be when firmly grounded in an epic or mythic context?<br>
<br>
Various game mechanics have been put in place that enhance combat while deterring gratuitous or random PKing.  For instance, experience points gained from victory are based on levels, and only a peer or higher level character will yield any significant gain. <br>
<br>
The traditional PKs of other games are outsiders who wander from region to region in search of prey, vanishing when their victims come looking for revenge. In Shadowbane, however, all players will belong to a Guild, run either by GMs or Players. Guilds are highly territorial, and you can easily learn where a character is from by viewing their Guild Crest when you click on them or by simply viewing your &quot;Recent Attacks&quot; log. Wanton murderers will be held accountable for their actions by the Guilds they serve, and the penalties for being expelled from a Guild are severe. Furthermore, trying to operate without the fixed home base that a Guild provides is asking for serious trouble. So, you may ask, what's to keep all the PKs from forming Guilds of their own? Nothing, but there's nothing to keep you and anyone ever troubled by them from forming your own Guilds, banding together, and battering the PK Guilds to dust. It's hard to hide a city, or a Tree of Life. Also, the reliance on Guilds means that every would-be victim has a Guild full of supporters to help them get even.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What is &quot;Bonding&quot;?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
A character is allowed to &quot;bond&quot; various items of equipment; these items must be equipped on the character's body (as opposed to being held in inventory).  Once bonded, a character cannot lose these items, even upon death.  When the character dies, the items will re-spawn with them at their Tree of Life.<br>
<br>
Banks also provide a mechanism for storing a limited number of items while not in use.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> PKers can loot and keep any UNbonded items you have</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What are the penalties of death?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
When a character dies, they will lose carried equipment (except for bonded items ) and experience. The amount of experience lost will vary based on the level of the monster (or character) that killed you. At low levels, or when a character is killed by an entity more powerful than themselves, the experience penalty will be slight. The opposite holds true as well: experience penalties will be higher if you are slain by something weaker (lower level) than yourself.  <br>
<br>
Players will always be able to keep  bound items when they die.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> When a character is killed, who has the looting rights?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
A character dies the items they had (other than those bonded) will remain on their corpse and can be taken by anyone in the area.  Don't worry, though, most equipment should be easy to replace, and in Shadowbane your character's combat effectiveness will be based far more on their skills and attributes than their weapon of choice. Finally, we've said it before, but it bears repeating: you'll always get to keep the three items bonded to your character. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Will there be custom moves and animations in combat?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Yes! Not only does each weapon type have it's own unique animations, many of the Powers (including special melee attacks such as Burning Blade, Piercing Strike, Reign of Steel, and Sword Song), whether Class or Discipline based, have their own unique moves and animations. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Does combat take any Player Skill or just Character Skill?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Anyone can level a character, equip some weapons and attack someone; this requires little skill. Effective use of Combat Maneuvers will determine the outcome of a fight. A higher level character with better equipment will lose to a player that uses his Combat Maneuvers more effectively. The basics are pretty obvious; there are a ton of these Maneuvers (with unique animations) that become available to different Classes at different levels and can be developed by investing skill points. Here are some important points: <br>
<br>
Maneuvers include one-shot moves that damage, blind, cripple, or otherwise hurt your opponent. Examples of these include: Kick, Backstab, Crippling Strike, Slam, and Power Strike. <br>
Maneuvers also include combat stances that affect the overall way your character performs in a fight. Among other things, these can modify Attack, Defense, and Damage ratings, and the rate at which Stamina is expended (or recovered). Examples include: Aggressive, All-Out Defense, Hold, Stand Ground, Recover, Withdraw, and Evade. <br>
Maneuvers cannot generally be stacked, so players must chose when and how to use them. <br>
Maneuvers either have a direct Stamina cost, or affect the way Stamina is lost in combat. This means that less robust or tired combatants need to end a fight quickly or disengage while they still have the energy to run away. <br>
Maneuvers have recycle times. This means that some moves can only be used once or twice during a given melee; knowing when to use a Maneuver is part of what makes a skilled player. <br>
Given experience, a player should be able to identify what Stances and Maneuvers his opponent is using, has used, or is about to use and change his tactics accordingly. <br>
